219	  <main id="main" class="wrap">
220	    <section id="what">
221	      <h2>What Scrum is</h2>
222	      <p>Scrum is a lightweight framework that helps teams deliver value through iterative work, frequent inspection, and adaptation. It defines a small set of accountabilities, events, and artifacts — and leaves the details of how the work gets done to the team.</p>
223	    </section>
224	
225	    <section id="when">
226	      <h2>When it helps</h2>
227	      <p>Scrum fits complex problems where requirements and solutions are uncertain and need to be discovered through delivery. It helps when a team needs a steady cadence to ship something useful, learn from it, and adjust — rather than committing up front to a fixed plan.</p>
228	    </section>
229	
230	    <section id="roles">
231	      <h2>Roles (accountabilities)</h2>
232	      <p class="lede">A Scrum Team has three accountabilities — together they own delivering value each Sprint.</p>
233	      <div class="grid">
234	        <article class="card">
235	          <h3>Product Owner</h3>
236	          <p>Accountable for maximizing the value of the product by managing the Product Backlog.</p>
237	        </article>
238	        <article class="card">
239	          <h3>Scrum Master</h3>
240	          <p>Accountable for the team's effectiveness and for establishing Scrum as defined in the Scrum Guide.</p>
241	        </article>
242	        <article class="card">
243	          <h3>Developers</h3>
244	          <p>Accountable for creating a usable Increment that meets the Definition of Done every Sprint.</p>
245	        </article>
246	      </div>
247	    </section>
248	
249	    <section id="events">
250	      <h2>Events</h2>
251	      <p class="lede">Five time-boxed events create regularity and remove the need for other meetings.</p>
252	      <div class="grid">
253	        <article class="card">
254	          <h3>Sprint</h3>
255	          <p>A fixed, time-boxed container (one month or less) inside which all the other Scrum events happen and an Increment is created.</p>
256	        </article>
257	        <article class="card">
258	          <h3>Sprint Planning</h3>
259	          <p>Initiates the Sprint by defining why it is valuable, what can be done, and how the chosen work will get done.</p>
260	        </article>
261	        <article class="card">
262	          <h3>Daily Scrum</h3>
263	          <p>A 15-minute event for Developers to inspect progress toward the Sprint Goal and adapt the plan for the next day.</p>
264	        </article>
265	        <article class="card">
266	          <h3>Sprint Review</h3>
267	          <p>Inspects the outcome of the Sprint with stakeholders and determines future adaptations to the Product Backlog.</p>
268	        </article>
269	        <article class="card">
270	          <h3>Sprint Retrospective</h3>
271	          <p>Closes the Sprint by planning ways to increase quality and effectiveness in how the team works together.</p>
272	        </article>
273	      </div>
274	    </section>
275	
276	    <section id="artifacts">
277	      <h2>Artifacts</h2>
278	      <p class="lede">Each artifact represents work or value, and each has a commitment that gives it focus.</p>
279	      <div class="grid">
280	        <article class="card">
281	          <h3>Product Backlog</h3>
282	          <p>An ordered list of what is needed to improve the product. Its commitment is the Product Goal.</p>
283	        </article>
284	        <article class="card">
285	          <h3>Sprint Backlog</h3>
286	          <p>The plan by and for the Developers — the Sprint Goal, the selected Product Backlog items, and how to deliver them.</p>
287	        </article>
288	        <article class="card">
289	          <h3>Increment</h3>
290	          <p>A concrete step toward the Product Goal. Each Increment is additive to all prior Increments and must be usable.</p>
291	        </article>
292	        <article class="card">
293	          <h3>Definition of Done</h3>
294	          <p>The shared standard of quality an Increment must meet to be considered complete and releasable.</p>
295	        </article>
296	      </div>
297	    </section>
298	
299	    <section id="sprint">
300	      <h2>The Sprint: a time-boxed container</h2>
301	      <p>The Sprint is the heartbeat of Scrum. It is a fixed-length cycle, one month or less, during which the team turns ideas into a usable Increment. Sprint Planning opens it, the Daily Scrum keeps it on track, and the Sprint Review and Retrospective close it — same length, same rhythm, every time.</p>
