356	        <figcaption id="flow-caption">Roles run the Events; the Events shape and produce the Artifacts. The Sprint is the time-boxed container around all of it.</figcaption>
357	      </figure>
358	    </section>
359	
360	    <section id="myths">
361	      <h2>Myths</h2>
362	      <p class="lede">A few common misconceptions, set straight against the Scrum Guide.</p>
363	      <div class="grid">
364	        <article class="card">
365	          <h3>Scrum is not a methodology with fixed scope agreed up front</h3>
366	          <p>Scrum is a lightweight framework, not a fixed methodology. The Product Backlog is ordered and refined as the team learns; changing requirements are expected, not avoided.</p>
367	        </article>
368	        <article class="card">
369	          <h3>The Scrum Master is not a project manager who assigns tasks</h3>
370	          <p>The Scrum Master is a true leader who serves the Scrum Team and the wider organization. Developers self-manage how the Sprint work gets done.</p>
371	        </article>
372	        <article class="card">
373	          <h3>The Daily Scrum is not a status meeting for managers</h3>
374	          <p>It is a 15-minute event for the Developers to inspect progress toward the Sprint Goal and adapt the plan for the next day of work.</p>
375	        </article>
376	      </div>
377	    </section>
378	
379	    <section id="faq">
380	      <h2>FAQ</h2>
381	      <p class="lede">Short answers to questions that come up most often.</p>
382	      <article>
383	        <h3>How does Scrum relate to Agile?</h3>
384	        <p>Agile is the broader mindset described by the Agile Manifesto's values and principles. Scrum is one specific lightweight framework that embodies Agile. Using Scrum well means living those values, not just running the events.</p>
385	      </article>
386	      <article>
387	        <h3>How is Scrum different from Kanban at a glance?</h3>
388	        <p>Scrum uses fixed-length Sprints, three defined accountabilities, and a small set of events to inspect and adapt. Kanban focuses on visualizing flow and limiting work in progress, without prescribed roles or time-boxed iterations. Many teams blend ideas from both.</p>
389	      </article>
390	      <article>
391	        <h3>Who decides what is built?</h3>
392	        <p>The Product Owner. They are accountable for ordering the Product Backlog and maximizing the value of the product. Developers decide how to build the selected work; stakeholders inform decisions but do not set the order.</p>
393	      </article>
394	      <article>
395	        <h3>Can Scrum be used outside software?</h3>
396	        <p>Yes. Scrum is intentionally lightweight and applies to any complex work where empirical process control — transparency, inspection, and adaptation — helps a team deliver value.</p>
397	      </article>
